content:
## Enabling MFA

To configure and enable a virtual MFA device for use with your IAM user (console)

1. Sign in to the AWS Management Console.
2. On the right side of the navigation bar, choose your account name, and choose Security Credentials. If necessary, choose Continue to Security Credentials.

3.Then expand the Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) section on the page. Choose Assign MFA device.

4. You need to write your AWS username in the Device name section. For example ali.veli After writing, you can click next and continue.
Warning: If you write something different in this section, MFA activation cannot be done.

1. You need to have the QR scanned by the authentication application by clicking on Show QR code. In the MFA Code 1 box, enter the six-digit number that's currently displayed by the MFA device. Wait up to 30 seconds for the device to generate a new number, and then type the new six-digit number into the MFA Code 2 box. Then click on add mfa.

## How-To Delete The Old Access Key & Secret Access Key

You should delete the keys which is older than 90 days.

1. Sign in to the AWS Management Console.
2. On the right side of the navigation bar, choose your account name, and choose My Security Credentials. If necessary, choose Continue to My Security Credentials.

Choose My Security Credentials

Delete the old key which is older than 90 days

## How-To Create A New Access Key & Secret Access Key

Once you activate Multi-factor Authentication (MFA), you need a new access key and secret access key.

1. Sign in to the AWS Management Console.
2. On the right side of the navigation bar, choose your account name, and choose My Security Credentials. If necessary, choose Continue to My Security Credentials.

Choose My Security Credentials

3. Then expand Access keys for CLI, SDK, & API access section on the page. Choose Create access key.

4. Your new access key is now available. (You can also download the access key in .csv file format)

Setup the cloud storage connections for clusters. For Azure Blob connection, once the cluster is started, create a new notebook and run the script below to mount data. Give hard-coded container_name, storage_account and access_token. It’s a one-time process, no need to do it for every cluster. In this way, no-one will confront with a secret key in cluster config section. Finally encrouge people to read the data using just `/mnt/` as given sample below.

```
dbutils.fs.mount(
  source=f"wasbs://{container_name}@{storage_account}.blob.core.windows.net",
  mount_point=f"/mnt/{container_name}",
  extra_configs={
    f"fs.azure.account.key.{storage_account}.blob.core.windows.net": access_token,
  }
)

spark.read.csv(f"/mnt/container_name/{key}.csv")

### Azure based Databricks deployment

- Navigate to Azure → Key vault → “invent-databricks-vault“ → Properties (Vault URI and Resource ID will be needed)
- Navigate to related Databricks deployment’s main entrance and change the url by adding #secrets/createScope to the end. Example URL:  https://adb-11111111111.19.azuredatabricks.net/?o=11111111111#secrets/createScopeScope name: credentials (not strict but this name is common in our DBX deployments. dbutils refers to this name)Manage principal: All users (might not be optional according to chosen tier)DNS Name: YOUR_VAULT_URI (most probably: https://invent-databricks-vault.vault.azure.net)Resource ID: YOUR_VAULT_RESOURCE_ID (similar to: /subscriptions/SUBSCRIPTION_ID/resourceGroups/RESOURCE_GROUP_NAME/providers/Microsoft.KeyVault/vaults/invent-databricks-vault)Create the scope.dbutils.secrets.get(scope='credentials', key=NAME_OF_THE_SECRET) could verify the connection.

There’s a separate AWS Dev account created for Invent developers and data scientists for development and test activities in an isolated environment without impacting any resource and workflows in AWS production environments.

To switch to this account, the user can select “Switch Role” option from the upper right corner menu in AWS console and enter the following information to define the “dev” role.

Account: 924947995844
Role:DevAccountAccessRole
Display Name:any name (such as “user-dev-role”)

Please give feedback to Alpha team in case there’s any access issue with the role on the Dev account. The permissions and policies defined for DevAccountAccessRole can be reviewed and expanded based on these requests.

et
import ssl
from datetime import datetime

ssl_notAfter_date_format: str = r'%b %d %H:%M:%S %Y %Z'

def get_ssl_data(host, port=443, timeout=5):
    context = ssl.create_default_context()
    conn = context.wrap_socket(socket.socket(socket.AF_INET), server_hostname=host)
    try:
        conn.settimeout(timeout)
        conn.connect((host, port))
        cert = conn.getpeercert()
        return cert
    finally:
        conn.close()

def get_ssl_expiration_time(host, port=443, timeout=5):
    cert = get_ssl_data(host, port, timeout)
    return datetime.strptime(cert['notAfter'], ssl_notAfter_date_format)

def get_ssl_time_remaining_day(host):
    return (get_ssl_expiration_time(host) - datetime.now()).days

print(get_ssl_data('tableau.inventanalytics.com'))
```

[new.inventanalytics.com](http://new.inventanalytics.com) is responded over EC2 directly.

content:
There’s a separate AWS Staging account created for Invent Staging delopers and data scientists for Development and test activities in an isolated environment without impacting any resource and workflows in AWS production environments.

To switch to this account, the user can select “Switch Role” option from the upper right corner menu in AWS console and enter the following information to define the “Staging” role.

Account: 165820428786
Role: StagingAccountAccessRoleDisplay Name:any name (such as “user-Staging-role”)

Please give feedback to #Alpha team in case there’s any access issue with the role on the Staging account. The permissions and policies defined for StagingAccountAccessRole can be reviewed and expanded based on these requests.

---

## Using Staging Role in AWS CLI

Add the following lines to .aws/credentials

```
[staging]
role_arn = arn:aws:iam::165820428786:role/StagingAccountAccessRole
source_profile = default
```

metadata.title: Switching Role for AWS Staging Account

content:
ing]
role_arn = arn:aws:iam::165820428786:role/StagingAccountAccessRole
source_profile = default
```

To test if it is configured OK you can use the following command:

```
aws --profile dev sts get-caller-identity
```

For programmatic access, you can use the approach below

```
CREDENTIALS=$(aws sts assume-role --role-arn arn:aws:iam::165820428786:role/StagingAccountAccessRole --role-session-name StagingAccountAccess)
export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=$(echo $CREDENTIALS | jq -r .Credentials.AccessKeyId)
export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=$(echo $CREDENTIALS | jq -r .Credentials.SecretAccessKey)
export AWS_SESSION_TOKEN=$(echo $CREDENTIALS | jq -r .Credentials.SessionToken)
<YOUR STUFF>
unset AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID
unset AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY
unset AWS_SESSION_TOKEN

```

content:
1 - Go to the Center of Excellence Confluence page. https://invent.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/COE

2-  Start copying the Project Page as shown below.

3 - Select the space and its underlying documents to be copied, as shown in the image. Then, proceed by clicking “Next.”

4 - Enter the customer’s Confluence document name in the “Start all titles with:” field. Then, click the “Copy” button.

5 - Verify that all the pages have been completely copied.

6 - Since the person who copied the project will be the owner of all the new files, it is necessary to change the owners of all the files as shown in the image below. We can proceed by selecting the project manager or an authorized user from the project as the owner.

After completing all these steps, we finalize the process by reviewing the copied files and ensuring everything is in order.

metadata.title: How to Use Deep Clone in Jira Project Template to Copy Tasks to Customer Project

content:
In this document, we will go over how to create an internal Jira project while onboarding a customer.

We have prepared a template project for you to use. By using the Deep Clone application, you can easily create a new project with this template. The steps to do so are outlined below.

1. Go to Jira

Visit: [https://invent.atlassian.net/jira/](https://invent.atlassian.net/jira/)

1. Select Deep Clone App

In the top menu, click on the Apps section and select the Deep Clone App.

1. Click on the “Project Clone” section.

1. Configure the settings as shown below:

- Source Project: Select Default Customer Internal Project Template (This must be selected as the template).
- Project Key: Choose an appropriate abbreviation for the new project.
- Project Name: Use the customer’s name. For example: Liwa, Liwa Replenishment, etc.
- All other configuration settings should be as shown below.

Finally, click on Clone Project to proceed.

1. Search for the project and navigate to the project page.

1. Since the board is not automatically created when creating a project via Deep Clone, we need to follow the steps below to create a new board. Go to the project section and select Board > Create board.

1. Since some settings cannot be transferred directly to the project, there are a few tasks to complete. To do this, go to Project Settings from the menu on the left side of the project.

content:
Azure databrickslerde invent-prod-eu-vault altından otomatik okuyor işlem yapmaya gerek yok. Fakat  aws databrickslerde aşağıdaki işlemlerin yapılması lazım.

Hem scope hem key yoksa aşağıdaki kod:

"string_value": "" (invent-prod-eu-vault altında yer alan tableau-databricks-workflow-token değeri.
pat_token = "" your pat token.

```py
import requests

workspace_url = "https://inventanalytics-teknosav2.cloud.databricks.com/"
pat_token = ""

headers = {"Authorization": f"Bearer {pat_token}"}

# 1. Scope oluşturma (credentials scope)
scope_data = {
    "scope": "credentials",
    "initial_manage_principal": "users"  # ya da belirli bir grup/rol
}

create_scope_response = requests.post(
    f"{workspace_url}/api/2.0/secrets/scopes/create",
    headers=headers,
    json=scope_data
)
print("Create Scope:", create_scope_response.status_code, create_scope_response.text)

ing a new user directory on /home/. directory when a new user logs in.

content:
1. Creation of a new project using the default template via the Deep Clone plugin.

1. Create Jira customer groups in the format shown below.Add the internal users provided by the project manager to the group named Team Alo Yoga Client Service (formatted as such).When inviting external users, add them to the group Alo Yoga Client Service Users, as provided by the project manager.

def create_cognito_client(domain_name):
    """AWS CLI kullanarak Cognito user pool client oluştur"""
    cmd = [
        "aws", "cognito-idp", "create-user-pool-client",
        "--user-pool-id", USER_POOL_ID,
        "--client-name", domain_name,
        "--generate-secret",
        "--allowed-o-auth-flows", "client_credentials",
        "--allowed-o-auth-scopes", RESOURCE_SCOPE,
        "--allowed-o-auth-flows-user-pool-client",
        "--region", AWS_REGION,
        "--output", "json"
    ]
    result = subprocess.run(cmd, capture_output=True, text=True)
    if result.returncode != 0:
        raise Exception(f"Error creating Cognito client: {result.stderr}")
    data = json.loads(result.stdout)
    return data["UserPoolClient"]["ClientId"], data["UserPoolClient"]["ClientSecret"]

def store_in_azure(vault_url, secret_name, client_id, client_secret):
    """Azure Key Vault'a secret ekle/güncelle"""
    credential = DefaultAzureCredential()
    kv_client = SecretClient(vault_url=vault_url, credential=credential)
    secret_value = json.dumps({"client_id": client_id, "client_secret": client_secret})
    kv_client.set_secret(secret_name, secret_value)
    print(f"Secret {secret_name} stored in Azure vault {vault_url}.")

# -------------------------------

for env, domain in ENVIRONMENTS.items():

    # Cognito client oluştur

Users open a task according to the document below, and once their managers approve, the following actions are performed by Eren Şahin. We only provide users with access to the secret.

This guideline has been prepared to be used in situations where Eren Şahin is not available.

 [How to Submit an AI API Key Request]

Best Practices

- Do not allow personal tokens. Create team/project tokens.

- Do not use general projects (exception: we have a single invent-gemini project on Google Gemini). Use Team / Project level Projects.

- Never share plain API keys. Share them via Secret Managers like AWS Secret Manager and Azure Key Vault. Users should access the API keys with their roles.

- Align with Sonic Team (Eren Şahin) for new API key requests and project / budget settings.

# OpenAI

OpenAI API keys are managed through the [OpenAI Platform](https://platform.openai.com/) Dashboard page.

### Step-1: Check Existing Projects

Click to project selector dropdown and select Manage Projects.

metadata.title: How to Create an AI API Key

content:
### Step-1: Check Existing Projects

Click to project selector dropdown and select Manage Projects.

In the projects page, check if there’s a relevant project for the team and project.

### Step-2: Create Project (Skip if a relevant project exists)

Click the Create button in the Projects page.

Then enter a proper Project name. Project name should represent the project scope (e.g. Sonic Development, Sonic Production etc)

### Step-3: Create API Key Under Project

Firstly, select the relevant project for API Key generation.

Go to the APIkeyspage under the Projectsection. Do not use the Organization level API keys.

Then click to Create New Secret Key

In the opened pop-up, you should first select “Service account” for Key owner settings.

Then enter a meaningful Service Key Name. Usually Project + Environment + API Key is a good convention.

Make sure that the relevant project is selected.

# Gemini

metadata.title: How to Create an AI API Key

content:
ironment + API Key is a good convention.

Make sure that the relevant project is selected.

# Gemini

OpenAI API keys are managed through the [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com/projects).

Note thatwe are using a single project for Gemini, invent-gemini. So you should create new API Keys Under invent-geminiproject.

### Step-1: Verify Project Access

First of all, verify that you can access the invent-geminiprojectunder the Projects page. If the projects are not listed, you need to import them once.

### Step-2: Create API Key

Go to the API Keys page using the menu in the sidebar on the left of the page. Then click to the Create API Key button.

In the opened pop-up, enter the API Key and make sure invent-gemini project is selected.

# Creating a Secret After Key Generation

We usually prefer using AWS Secrets Manager for role/user based secret management. After you create an API key, you should create a new secret in Secrets Manager.

metadata.title: How to Create an AI API Key

content:
d secret management. After you create an API key, you should create a new secret in Secrets Manager.

Use the following naming convention unless another secret name is explicitly asked for:

ai_access_keys/<project_name>/<ai_provider_openai_or_gemini>

The key content should be the JSON structure below:

{"api_key": "<paste-api-key-here>"}



### Step-1: Choose Secret type

Select “other type of secret” and enter the secret content as key/value pairs.

Enter secret name, description, and tags.

Make sure that you enter the tags below:

○      Project: <Project Name>

○      Customer: <Customer Name>

○      AI Provider: <OpenAI or Gemini>

○      Environment: <Dev, Prod>

○      ServerType: <ServerType>

○      Team: <Team Name>

Refer to [LLM API Key Creation Policy](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1L32dM2dyzRTRToJSdW_-Ugw1BdxgzWW-2baz-bjMCdc/edit?tab=t.0) for more details.

# Executive Summary

This project aims to address the limitations of the current VPN infrastructure that affect network performance for users outside the Istanbul Office. The initiative will begin by evaluating and implementing short-term mitigation solutions. If these mitigations can be applied with minimal effort, they will be prioritized first; otherwise, the project will proceed directly to long-term architectural improvements to enhance VPN speed and stability for all users.

# Problem Statement

The company currently operates two VPN solutions:

- FortiClient VPN hosted in Istanbul Office
- AWS VPN in Ireland Region

This infrastructure configuration results in:

- Lower bandwidth availability for users
- Reduced Internet speed in user networks (except Istanbul Office)
- Inconsistent VPN performance across different geographical locations

# Goal & Objectives

This document has been created to guide the handling of AWS access requests from any user or team.

It covers only Invent user permissions. Service accounts and customer accounts are managed separately via AWS IAM. Permissions for Invent users and their teams fall within the scope of this document.

Note: Individual permissions will not be granted based solely on incoming requests. Permissions are updated only through the team leader’s approval by modifying the team’s permission set.

## Example

If a user is part of the Apex team and uses the Apex team role in AWS, any updates related to this role must be submitted to their manager for approval. Once approved, the permission set for the Apex role will be updated. Permissions are extended or restricted at the team level, not individually.

## 5. Create OS specific Inventories for mass deployments

We need to create an inventory for both Linux and Windows servers to differentiate them. The reason for inventory management is basically a “configuration management”.

Inventories define *which hosts* Ansible will manage, and store connection details like variables and credentials. Inventory Groups let you organize those hosts into logical collections (e.g., web, db, prod), so you can target specific subsets when running playbooks. This structure makes automation cleaner, scalable, and easier to manage.

As per our usage intensity as Alpha there will not be a necessity to create a VM with large compute power. We have decided to install Ansible tower on the [i-08e1337c7d3925d3f (Ansible-Server)](https://eu-west-1.console.aws.amazon.com/ec2/home?region=eu-west-1#InstanceDetails:instanceId=i-08e1337c7d3925d3f) on EC2 - Ireland.The instance has 4 vcpu’s in total. 2 will be allocated for AWX and the remaining 2 will be used for playbook deployments.

For this lightweight installation we will be managing the installation via Minikube.

Note that the installation is designed for Ubuntu 22.04 and it may require version updates for depencies with newer distros.

## Phase 1: Base Infrastructure Setup

First, we install the container Docker and the Kubernetes orchestration tools.

```bash
# Prepare VM
sudo apt update && sudo apt install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg lsb-release conntrack socat git

metadata.title: AWX - VM Installation guide

VM

# Add Docker Repo
sudo mkdir -p /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
echo "deb [arch=$(dpkg --print-architecture) signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu $(lsb_release -cs) stable" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list > /dev/null

# Install Docker Engine
sudo apt update && sudo apt install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-compose-plugin

# Add your user to the docker group, use ansible_user
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
newgrp docker
```

# Download & Install Minikube
curl -LO https://storage.googleapis.com/minikube/releases/latest/minikube-linux-amd64

ikube/releases/latest/minikube-linux-amd64

## Phase 2: Host Networking Configuration (Crucial)

> Note: To allow AWX pods to route traffic out of the cluster to reach your Windows Servers on the VPN/VPC, we must enable IP forwarding on the Ubuntu host. If you miss this step you will have to destory the existing pods and install from scratch. To prevent data loss be sure to apply this step.

```bash
#Enable Kernel forwarding
echo 1 | sudo tee /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward
#Configure ubuntu firewall for routing
sudo ufw default allow routed
sudo ufw reload
```

## Phase 3: Cluster Initialization & Persistence

metadata.title: AWX - VM Installation guide

content:
sudo ufw default allow routed
sudo ufw reload
```

## Phase 3: Cluster Initialization & Persistence

We do not start Minikube manually. We create a Systemd service to ensure it starts on boot with the specific Calico CNI configuration to avoid IP conflicts. (Calico for AWX <> Target VM visibility)

Create the Service File: `sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/minikube.service`

```bash
[Unit]
Description=Minikube Cluster
After=docker.service
Requires=docker.service

[Service]
Type=oneshot
RemainAfterExit=yes
User=ansible_user
Group=docker

# THE CRITICAL FIX:
# 1. --cni=calico : Uses Calico instead of default bridge
# 2. --extra-config : Forces Internal IP range to 192.168.0.0/16 to avoid 10.x.x.x conflict
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/minikube start --driver=docker --cpus=2 --memory=6g --addons=ingress --cni=calico --extra-config=kubeadm.pod-network-cidr=192.168.0.0/16

ExecStop=/usr/local/bin/minikube stop

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
```

Start the cluster:

metadata.title: AWX - VM Installation guide

content:
ExecStop=/usr/local/bin/minikube stop

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
```

Start the cluster:

```bash
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable minikube
sudo systemctl start minikube
```

Verify Network CIDR: Ensure the conflict is resolved by checking the Pod CIDR.

```
kubectl get nodes -o jsonpath='{.items[*].spec.podCIDR}'
# Expected Output: 192.168.0.0/16 (or similar 192.168 range)
```

> Info: If above output is in 10.X.X.X you will have network routing conflict. See 2. comment on minikube.service file.

## Phase 4: AWX Installation

Create Installer Directory:

```
mkdir -p ~/awx-install && cd ~/awx-install
```

Create `kustomization.yaml`:

```yaml
apiVersion: kustomize.config.k8s.io/v1beta1
kind: Kustomization
resources:
  - github.com/ansible/awx-operator/config/default?ref=2.19.1
  - awx-deployment.yaml
images:
  - name: quay.io/ansible/awx-operator
    newTag: 2.19.1
namespace: awx
```

awx-deployment.yaml:

metadata.title: AWX - VM Installation guide

content:
:
  - name: quay.io/ansible/awx-operator
    newTag: 2.19.1
namespace: awx
```

awx-deployment.yaml:

```yaml
---
apiVersion: awx.ansible.com/v1beta1
kind: AWX
metadata:
  name: awx-demo
spec:
  service_type: NodePort
  postgres_storage_class: standard
```

Deploy AWX:

```
kubectl apply -k .
# Wait for pods to be ready (approx 5-10 mins)
kubectl get pods -n awx -w
```

## Phase 5: External Access (Port Forwarding)

To make the AWX UI accessible from the VPC network (not just localhost), we create a second Systemd service.

Create the Service File: `sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/awx-expose.service`

```
[Unit]
Description=Expose AWX on Host Port 8080
After=minikube.service
Requires=minikube.service

[Service]
User=ansible_user
Restart=always
RestartSec=10
# Binds to 0.0.0.0 so traffic from the VPC can reach the container
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/kubectl port-forward --address 0.0.0.0 svc/awx-demo-service -n awx 8080:80

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
```

Start Access Service:

metadata.title: AWX - VM Installation guide

content:
svc/awx-demo-service -n awx 8080:80

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
```

Start Access Service:

```
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable awx-expose
sudo systemctl start awx-expose
```

Tools:

Active Directory
Okta

Azure (Office365)
Datadog
Drata

Users are created in Active Directory. After being created in Active Directory, they are integrated with Okta via the Okta agent.

Datadog:

The Datadog application is integrated with Okta for SSO, and authorization is managed via Okta groups.

All Invent employees are granted read-only access by default.

If elevated access is required, a permission request is submitted and the user’s role group is updated accordingly.

Drata:

The Drata application is assigned to all Invent employees via Okta, providing SSO-based login access.

Drata is a compliance automation tool that streamlines and accelerates SOC 1, SOC 2, and ISO 27001 compliance processes.

We are planning Identity Management in two phases:

Phase 1 – User Onboarding & Offboarding (Permanent Access):

metadata.title: Identity Management Current Status

content:
ning Identity Management in two phases:

Phase 1 – User Onboarding & Offboarding (Permanent Access):

In this phase, every user will be assigned to predefined team and role-based groups during onboarding, ensuring they receive their default, permanent access rights.

Similarly, during offboarding, users will be automatically removed from these groups to revoke all associated accesses.

This phase defines and manages baseline, permanent access across the organization.

Phase 2 – Temporary / Just-in-Time Access:

This phase covers the process for granting temporary roles during incident or emergency situations.

Access will be time-bound, approved, and automatically revoked after the defined period, ensuring controlled and auditable privilege escalation when required.

metadata.title: Google Workspace User Onboard Roadmap

content:
This document has been created to inform Apex team members about the Okta–Google Workspace integration and to help ensure the integration operates smoothly without any issues.

This document has been created to inform Apex team members about the Okta–Google Workspace integration and to help ensure the integration operates smoothly without any issues:

# OKTA Side:

1- User Creation:

During user creation, the user will be added to their corresponding Google Workspace OU group.

- This will create the user account.
- Required licenses will be assigned.
- The user will be placed into the relevant Google Workspace OU.

You can find the related guidance in the document linked below.
[Google Workspace User Onboard Roadmap]

2- User Group Assignment:

After the user is created by being assigned to the application as described in item 1, the user can then be added to the requested Google Workspace groups via Okta.

metadata.title: Apex Roadmap

content:
s described in item 1, the user can then be added to the requested Google Workspace groups via Okta.

Note: Any group assignment performed without completing step 1 will be invalid, as the user will not yet exist. User creation applies only to new users; all existing users have already been migrated to Okta as part of the integration and are fully synchronized.

Note: Group-to-group assignment will be performed on the Google Workspace side as described.

3- Google Group Creation:

User groups will now be created in Okta and then pushed to Google Workspace.

After a Google group is created in Okta, it can be provisioned using the Group Push feature within the Google Workspace application.

Pushed groups derive their email addresses from the group name. For example:

A group pushed with the name “Invent XXX Team” will be created with the email address [invent_xxx_team@invent.ai](mailto:invent_xxx_team@invent.ai).

metadata.title: Apex Roadmap

content:
ill be created with the email address [invent_xxx_team@invent.ai](mailto:invent_xxx_team@invent.ai).

Note: Group creation must be performed only through Okta. Creating groups directly in Google Workspace may cause synchronization issues with the integration.

4 - User Deactivation:

To deactivate a user account, removing the user from the OktaGoogle Workspace App user group will suspend the user’s Google Workspace account and revoke the assigned licenses.

Additionally, removing the user from any pushed groups will terminate the corresponding group memberships.

# Google Workspace Side:

1- Adding a Group to a Google Workspace Group:

To assign one user group to another group, the operation must be performed in the Google Workspace Admin Console. This action cannot be done through Okta.

Operations That Can Be Performed on the Google Workspace Side:

content:
action cannot be done through Okta.

Operations That Can Be Performed on the Google Workspace Side:

All operations outside of the steps explicitly defined for the Okta side will continue to be performed through the Google Workspace Admin Console.

Example:

Google Workspace Mail Log Search, Mail Routing etc.

Note:

If a Google Workspace user needs to be created outside of Okta, the steps below must be followed:

Invent Users Out of Okta
For an Invent employee who is not managed through Okta, the following steps must be completed:

1. The user must be created in Google Workspace and the appropriate license must be assigned. A temporary password should be set.
2. The user must be added to the No Okta, Access Drive (Internal) organizational unit. (This ensures that the user remains outside of Okta management.)

With this approach, the user is created outside of Okta and is able to access email without being managed by Okta.

External Users Out of Okta

tside of Okta and is able to access email without being managed by Okta.

External Users Out of Okta

For an External users who is not managed through Okta, the following steps must be completed:

1. The user must be created in Google Workspace and the appropriate license must be assigned. A temporary password should be set.
2. The user must be added to the Subcontractors (External, No OKTA) organizational unit. (This ensures that the user remains outside of Okta management.)

With this approach, the user is created outside of Okta and is able to access email without being managed by Okta.

- Adding token to the script:Open the Google Sheet Prod.Go to Extensions → Apps Script → Project Settings → Script Properties.Add the following keys:ATLASSIAN_EMAIL → fatih.bahceci@invent.aiATLASSIAN_API_TOKEN → <paste token here>ATLASSIAN_DOMAIN → invent.atlassian.netSave changes.
